	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105035380944?origin=resultslist},
	abstract = {Controlled Environment Agriculture (CEA) faces challenges in accessing precise, actionable knowledge for efficient production management. Traditional expert systems and search engines often lack the flexibility and contextual understanding needed to address complex queries. Large language models (LLMs) exhibit strong generative and comprehension abilities, presenting an opportunity to enhance CEA practices. This study proposes ChatCEA, an intelligent service agent that integrates LLMs with domain-specific knowledge through a Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) framework. The framework includes three main components: a two-source knowledge base module built from management manuals and journal papers, a retrieval module for contextual semantic search, and a knowledge integration module for processing unstructured data and refining information matching. This structure supplements general LLMs with specialized domain knowledge to improve response accuracy and relevance. ChatCEA also establishes the first CEA-specific benchmark with 1,025 question–answer pairs. The benchmark includes both qualitative and quantitative questions and supports systematic evaluation across the main subdomains of the entire production process. The framework also supports local deployment to protect data privacy and enable practical use in production environments. Experimental results show that ChatCEA achieves an answer correctness rate of 0.71, while GPT-4 and Google Search reach 0.41 and 0.44, respectively. The LLM-based evaluation scores are 4.3 for ChatCEA, 3.8 for GPT-4, and 2.5 for Google Search. ChatCEA also improved the handling of quantitative questions by extracting and reasoning with numerical information. These results demonstrate that ChatCEA provides accurate, data-driven support for CEA management. The knowledge base, Q&A benchmark, and source code are available at https://github.com/IDEAS-ZJU/ChatCEA. © 2026 Elsevier B.V.},
